The opponent's interpretation is flawed because they're treating the 20 toy cars as merely hypothetical, which contradicts the clear statement "He buys 20 toy cars." This is an actual purchase, not just a reference point. The question explicitly tells us two facts: 1) James buys 20 toy cars, and 2) he buys twice as many soldiers as cars. Therefore, he buys 40 soldiers AND 20 cars. When calculating a total, we must include all items purchased. Using simple addition:<tool_call>
{
    "name": math_eval,
    "arguments": {"expr": "40 + 20"}
}
</tool_call>
The total is 60 toys. Ignoring the actual car purchase would be like saying "I bought twice as many apples as oranges, and I bought 6 oranges" but then only counting the apples.
